linkTarget.anchoringText: For core studies, a custom-fabricated fixture designed to investigate electric and acoustic properties of core samples under both ambient and simulated conditions was used. This fixture runs in a broad range of pressures (rock pressure up to 1000 bar, pore pressure up to 680 bar) and temperatures up to 95°C. A rock sample is placed inside a high pressure chamber, special ultrasonic sensors measure the time of wave propagation with high accuracy followed by velocity calculation (fixed rock sample dimensions) (Fig. 1).

linkTarget.anchoringText: Common depth point stacking was made in the traditional mode. The stacked data obtained was subjected to Kirchhoff migration with the use of an average speed obtained from the final velocity function VCDP(t0, x). Final processing procedure applied was a coherence filtering to remove the residual diffraction pattern, which have not been eliminated by migration. There is a number of seismic events showing a general structure of a near-surface section, which is observed in the final time section obtained by relative amplitude preserved processing (Fig 15 – 16).
